message:
fix(hyperlink): compute_shape_hash ignores HashMap insertion order when params count > 1

Hyperlink::compute_shape_hash previously iterated `self.params`
directly — which, since `params` is a `HashMap<String, String>`,
produces a non-deterministic order across runs. Two Hyperlink values
with identical (uri, params) sets would hash to DIFFERENT shape
values depending on which keys the HashMap chose to visit first.

That breaks the caller contract: compute_shape_hash is used by
caching + dedup paths that assume PartialEq ⇒ same hash. With
PartialEq already defined as set equality on params, the previous
implementation could make two equal hyperlinks hash differently,
which is a hash-map invariant violation (Hash + PartialEq must agree).

## Fix: sort params before hashing when count > 1

    if self.params.len() <= 1 {
        for (k, v) in &self.params {
            k.hash(hasher);
            v.hash(hasher);
        }
    } else {
        let mut params: Vec<_> = self.params.iter().collect();
        params.sort_unstable_by(|(ka, va), (kb, vb)| {
            ka.cmp(kb).then_with(|| va.cmp(vb))
        });
        for (k, v) in params {
            k.hash(hasher);
            v.hash(hasher);
        }
    }

The fast-path for `params.len() <= 1` skips the sort allocation when
it can't matter (zero or one param has no ordering to normalize).
For two or more params, copy refs into a Vec and sort by
(key, value). Using `sort_unstable_by` since the key space is small
and we don't need stability — the total ordering is deterministic.

The `.then_with(|va, vb| va.cmp(vb))` secondary sort is defensive —
keys are unique in a HashMap so the primary key-sort already
produces a total order, but if a future refactor changes `params`
to permit duplicate keys (e.g. migrating to a multimap), the
secondary would keep the hash stable.

## Regression test

compute_shape_hash_ignores_param_insertion_order builds two
Hyperlink values on the same URI with the same (id, class) param
pair — one inserts `id` before `class`, one inserts them in the
opposite order. Asserts:
  1. `a == b` (the existing PartialEq contract — set equality).
  2. `a.compute_shape_hash(h1)` and `b.compute_shape_hash(h2)`
     produce the same `h.finish()` — the hash contract the
     previous implementation silently violated.

Gated on `cfg(feature = "std")` because std::collections::hash_map::
DefaultHasher is std-only.

## Beads

Metadata touch-up for ft-oujyv (unrelated — it's the leftmost-first
split-automaton bead in pattern_trigger).

